Questions:

1. Is there a limit on the number of "processors"? If, say for example, we're limited to 1 processor, then the execution time is always the same for any graph since we have to compute each task linearly.
2. Is the graph a single connected component? In other words, can we have something like [(n1, n2), (n3, n4)]?
3. Is the graph valid? e.g. cycles in the graph?

Assuming there's no cycles within the graph and all nodes are a single component:

```python

def minExecTime(deps: List[Tuple[int, int]], execTime: List[int]) -> int:
    if not deps or not execTime: return 0

    graph = defaultdict(list)
    in_degrees = defaultdict(int)
    for src, dst in deps: 
        graph[src].append(dst)
        in_degrees[dst] += 1

    q = deque()
    for i, degree in in_degrees:
        if degree == 0 : q.append(i)
    q.append(None)

    total_time = cur_level_time = 0
    while q:
        cur = q.popleft()
        if cur:
            cur_level_time = max(cur_level_time, execTime[cur])
            for dep in graph[cur]:
                in_degrees[dep] -= 1
                if in_degrees[dep] == 0: q.append(dep)
        else:
            total_time += cur_level_time
            cur_level_time = 0
            if q: q.append(None)

    return total_time
```

Assumptions:
- We have at least "N" processors for parallel work, where N = Num of Vertices
- No cycle in the graph

Some observation:
- There can be multiple acyclic graphs => globalTime = Max (Individual acyclic graphs)
- For Individual graphs => At each level from the node, Time  = Time + PreviousTime, where PreviousTime will be the max at it's level.

```
// O (V + E)
public int minimumTimeForTaskCompletion (Map<Integer, Integer> taskTime, Map<Integer, Integer> dependencies, int numNodes) {

	// Create a adjaceny matrix
	Map<Integer, List<Integer>> adjMatrix = new HashMap();
	for (int i=0; i<numNodes; i++) {
		adjMatrix.put(i, new ArrayList());
	}
	for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> entry : dependencies) {
		adjMatrix.get(entry.getKey()).add(entry.getValue());
	}

	// Find the roots
	// 0 -> root, 1 -> val
	int[] nodes = new int[numNodes];
	Set<Integer> roots = getRootNodes(adjMatrix, nodes);

	// Find the max time - loop and find the global max
	int globalTime;
	for (Integer r : roots) {
		int graphTime = getTime(taskTime, adjMatrix, r);
   		globalTime = Math.max(globalTime, graphTime);
	}

	return globalTime;
}

// Should do BFS here as we need to take Max time of all adjacent neighbors
// O (V + E)
public int getTime (Map<Integer, Integer> taskTime, Map<Integer, List<Integer>> adjMatrix, int root) {
	Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList();
	q.offer(root);
	int graphMax  = 0;
	while (!q.isEmpty()) {
		int localMax = 0;
		for (int i=0, sz = q.size(); i<sz; i++) {
			int currentNode = q.pop();
			int currentNodeTime = taskTime.get(currentNode);

			localMax = Math.max(localMax, currentNodeTime);

			for (Integer childNode: adjMatrix.get(currentNode)) {
				q.offer(childNode);
			}
		}
		graphMax = graphMax + localMax;
	}

	return graphMax;
}

// O (V + E)
public Set<Integer> getRootNodes (Map<Integer, List<Integer>> adjMatrix, int[] nodes) {
	Set<Integer> result = new HashSet();

	for (Map.Entry<Integer, List<Integer>> adj: adjMatrix) {
		if (nodes[adj.getKey()] == 0) {
			// not visited
			dfs(nodes[adj.getKey(), adjMatrix, nodes);
		}
	}

	for (Integer i: nodes) {
		if (i == 0) result.add(i);
	}

	return result;
}

public void dfs (int node, Map<Integer, List<Integer>> adjMatrix, int[] nodes) {
	// visited
	if (nodes[node] == 1) return;

	for (Integer child: adjMatrix.get(node)) {
		nodes[child] = 1;
		dfs(child, adjMatrix, nodes);
	}
}
